    content: "1. PRODUCTION CONCEPT (1900s): Focus on production efficiency and wide distribution. Consumers favor affordable and available products. Risk: marketing myopia.\n\n2. PRODUCT CONCEPT (1915-1920s): Focus on product quality, performance, and innovation. Companies make continuous product improvements. Risk: marketing myopia + 'better mousetrap' fallacy (assuming a superior product sells itself).\n\n3. SELLING CONCEPT (1930s): Focus on large-scale selling and promotion effort. Typically applied to unsought goods (insurance, encyclopedias). Risks: aggressive selling damages long-term customer relationships; focuses on transactions, not relationships.\n\n4. MARKETING CONCEPT (1950s-1960s): Focus on customer needs and delivering satisfaction more effectively and efficiently than competitors. 'Find the right customers for your product,' not the other way around. Revlon: 'We sell hope, not lipstick.'\n\n5. SOCIETAL MARKETING CONCEPT (1970s-present): Considers consumers' wants + company's requirements + society's long-run interests. Addresses conflicts between short-run consumer wants and long-run social welfare. Examples: eco-friendly packaging, ethical sourcing, anti-greenwashing.",
