    title: "Needs, Wants, Demands & Customer Value",
    content: "CORE MARKETING CONCEPTS:\n\nNEEDS: States of felt deprivation — physical (food, shelter), social (belonging, affection), individual (knowledge, self-expression). Needs are NOT created by marketers; they are inherent in human nature.\n\nWANTS: The form human needs take as shaped by culture and individual personality. A person needs food but wants a pizza or sushi depending on background and preferences.\n\nDEMANDS: Wants backed by buying power. When a customer can and will pay, a want becomes a demand.\n\nMARKETING MYOPIA (Theodore Levitt):\n- The mistake of paying more attention to the specific products offered than to the benefits and experiences those products create.\n- Classic example: railroad companies defined themselves as being in the 'railroad business' instead of the 'transportation business' — and lost customers to airlines, trucks, and cars.\n- The 'better mousetrap fallacy': assuming that if you build a superior product, the world will beat a path to your door. In reality, without understanding customer needs, even a great product can fail.\n\nCUSTOMER RELATIONSHIP MANAGEMENT (CRM):\n- The overall process of building and maintaining profitable customer relationships by delivering superior customer value and satisfaction.\n- CRM tools: loyalty programs, personalized communication, customer databases, social CRM (listening on social media).\n\nCUSTOMER SATISFACTION:\n- Based on expectancy disconfirmation theory: Satisfaction = f(Performance vs. Expectations).\n- P ≥ E → satisfied. P > E → delighted. P < E → dissatisfied.\n- Aim for delight, not just satisfaction — delighted customers become loyal advocates.\n\nCUSTOMER LIFETIME VALUE (CLV):\n- The entire stream of purchases a customer makes over a lifetime of patronage.\n- Formula concept: CLV = Average purchase value × Purchase frequency × Customer lifespan.\n- Losing a single customer means losing that entire future revenue stream.\n\nCUSTOMER EQUITY:\n- The total combined CLVs of ALL of a company's current and potential customers.\n- A forward-looking measure of the value of the company's customer base.\n- Better predictor of long-term performance than current sales or market share.\n- Three drivers: value equity (objective assessment), brand equity (subjective/emotional assessment), relationship equity (tendency to stick with the brand).",
